2 SENATE BILL 385
1 Section 18–112
2 Annotated Code of Maryland
3 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
4 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
5 Article – Health Occupations
6 Section 12–508
7 Annotated Code of Maryland
8 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
9 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
10 Article – Insurance
11 Section 15–1A–10 and 15–817
12 Annotated Code of Maryland
13 (2017 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
14 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
15 That Section(s) 18–328 through 18–332 and the part “Part V. Pertussis” of Article – Health
16 – General of the Annotated Code of Maryland be repealed.
17 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
18 as follows:
19 Article – Health – General
20 18–112.
21 (A) THE SECRETARY SHALL ISSUE RECOMMENDATIONS FOR
22 IMMUNIZATIONS, SCREENINGS, AND PREVENTIVE SERVICES FOR INFANTS,
23 CHILDREN, AND ADULTS THAT FOLLOW THE GENERALLY ACCEPTED CONSENSUS
24 WITHIN THE SCIENTIFIC COMMUNITY AND SOUND CLINICAL GUIDANCE AS
25 SPECIFIED IN SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION AND SUBJECT TO SUBSECTION (C)
26 OF THIS SECTION.
27 (B) THE RECOMMENDATIONS SHALL:
28 (1) BE MADE IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE APPLICABLE
29 RECOMMENDATIONS OF THE FOLLOWING AUTHORITATIVE MEDICAL
30 ORGANIZATIONS:
31 (I) THE AMERICAN ACADEMY OF PEDIATRICS;
32 (II) THE AMERICAN COLLEGE OF OBSTETRICIANS AND
33 GYNECOLOGISTS; OR

SENATE BILL 385 3
1 (III) THE AMERICAN ACADEMY OF FAMILY PHYSICIANS; AND
2 (2) TAKE INTO CONSIDERATION THE APPLICABLE GUIDANCE OF:
3 (I) THE MARYLAND STATEWIDE ADVISORY COMMISSION ON
4 IMMUNIZATIONS;
5 (II) THE U.S. DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND HUMAN
6 SERVICES, INCLUDING THE HEALTH RESOURCES AND SERVICES ADMINISTRATION;
7 (III) THE U.S. CENTERS FOR DISEASE CONTROL AND
8 PREVENTION, INCLUDING THE ADVISORY COMMITTEE ON IMMUNIZATION
9 PRACTICES;
10 (IV) THE U.S. FOOD AND DRUG ADMINISTRATION, INCLUDING
11 THE VACCINES AND RELATED BIOLOGICAL PRODUCTS ADVISORY COMMITTEE;
12 AND
13 (V) THE U.S. PREVENTIVE SERVICES TASK FORCE.
14 (C) BEFORE ADOPTING A RECOMMENDATION FOR A PREVENTIVE SERVICE
15 THAT IS NOT AN IMMUNIZATION AND HAS NOT RECEIVED A RECOMMENDATION FROM
16 THE U.S. DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES OR AN A OR B RATING
17 FROM THE U.S. PREVENTIVE SERVICES TASK FORCE, THE SECRETARY SHALL:
18 (1) HOLD A NOTICE AND COMMENT PERIOD OF AT LEAST 30 DAYS;
19 (2) OBTAIN AN ANALYSIS FROM THE MARYLAND HEALTH CARE
20 COMMISSION ON THE SERVICE THAT MEETS THE REQUIREMENTS OF § 15–1501 OF
21 THE INSURANCE ARTICLE; AND
22 (3) CITE THE APPLICABLE RECOMMENDATIONS OF THE
23 AUTHORITATIVE MEDICAL ORGANIZATIONS ON WHICH A RECOMMENDATION WOULD
24 BE BASED.
25 (C) (D) THE SECRETARY SHALL:
26 (1) PUBLISH RECOMMENDATIONS ISSUED UNDER THIS SECTION ON
27 THE DEPARTMENT’S WEBSITE; AND
28 (2) DISTRIBUTE THE RECOMMENDATIONS ISSUED UNDER THIS
29 SECTION TO LICENSED HEALTH PROFESSIONALS IN THE STATE AND TO THE
30 MARYLAND INSURANCE ADMINISTRATION.

4 SENATE BILL 385
1 Article – Health Occupations
2 12–508.
3 (a) (1) Subject to paragraph (4) of this subsection, a pharmacist may order and
4 administer a vaccination to an individual who is at least 3 years old if:
5 (i) The vaccine is:
6 1. An influenza vaccine;
7 2. A COVID–19 vaccine; or
8 3. Used in response to a public health emergency;
9 (ii) The pharmacist has completed a practical training program of at
10 least 20 hours that is approved by the Accreditation Council for Pharmacy Education and
11 includes:
12 1. Hands–on injection techniques;
13 2. Clinical evaluation of indications and contraindications of
14 vaccines; and
15 3. The recognition and treatment of emergency reactions to
16 vaccines;
17 (iii) The pharmacist has a current certificate in basic
18 cardiopulmonary resuscitation;
19 (iv) The pharmacist has completed a minimum of 2 hours of
20 continuing pharmaceutical education related to immunizations that is approved by the
21 Accreditation Council for Pharmacy Education as part of the license renewal requirements
22 under § 12–309 of this title;
23 (v) The pharmacist complies with the record–keeping and reporting
24 requirements in paragraph (5) of this subsection and any corresponding regulations
25 adopted by the Board; and
26 (vi) If the vaccination is administered to an individual under the age
27 of 18 years, the pharmacist informs the child vaccination patient and adult caregiver who
28 is accompanying the child of the importance of well–child visits with a pediatric primary
29 care provider and refers the patient to a pediatric primary care provider when appropriate.
30 (2) Subject to paragraph (4) of this subsection, a pharmacist who has met
31 the requirement of paragraph (1)(ii) through (vi) of this subsection may administer to an
32 individual who is at least 7 years old a vaccination that is:

SENATE BILL 385 5
1 (i) Recommended by the Centers for Disease Control and
2 Prevention’s Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices; [or]
3 (ii) Approved or authorized by the U.S. Food and Drug
4 Administration; OR
5 (III) RECOMMENDED BY THE SECRETARY OF HEALTH IN
6 ACCORDANCE WITH § 18–112 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE.
7 (3) Subject to paragraph (4) of this subsection, a pharmacist who has met
8 the requirement of paragraph (1)(ii), (iii), and (iv) of this subsection may administer to an
9 adult a vaccination that is recommended in the Centers for Disease Control and
10 Prevention’s Health Information for International Travel.
11 (4) [(i)] A pharmacist shall administer a vaccination under paragraph
12 (1), (2), or (3) of this subsection under a written protocol that:
13 [1.] (I) Is vaccine specific; and
14 [2.] (II) Meets criteria established by the Department, in
15 consultation with the Board, the Board of Physicians, and the Board of Nursing, in
16 regulation.
17 [(ii) The recommendations of the Centers for Disease Control and
18 Prevention’s Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices cited in this section refer to
19 federal statutes, rules, and guidance in effect:
20 1. On December 31, 2024; or
21 2. At a later date to account for any new vaccines
22 recommended by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention’s Advisory Committee on
23 Immunization Practices after December 31, 2024.]
24 (5) A pharmacist shall:
25 (i) Report all vaccinations administered by the pharmacist to the
26 ImmuNet Program established under § 18–109 of the Health – General Article;
27 (ii) If the vaccination has been administered in accordance with a
28 prescription, document at least one effort to inform the individual’s authorized prescriber
29 that the vaccination has been administered; and
30 (iii) Except for an influenza vaccination administered under
31 paragraph (1) of this subsection, if the authorized prescriber is not the individual’s primary
32 care provider or if the vaccination has not been administered in accordance with a

6 SENATE BILL 385
1 prescription, document at least one effort to inform the individual’s primary care provider
2 or other usual source of care that the vaccination has been administered.
3 (b) The Board shall:
4 (1) Set reasonable fees for the administration of vaccinations under this
5 section; and
6 (2) Adopt regulations that require a pharmacist to submit a registration
7 form to the Board that includes verification that the pharmacist:
8 (i) Has successfully completed a certification course approved by the
9 Board [that included instruction in the guidelines and recommendations of the Centers for
10 Disease Control and Prevention regarding vaccinations in effect on December 31, 2024];
11 and
12 (ii) Is certified in basic cardiopulmonary resuscitation and obtained
13 the certification through in–person classroom instruction.
14 Article – Insurance
15 15–1A–10.
16 (a) Subject to subsection (e) of this section and except as provided in subsections
17 (b), (c), and (d) of this section, a carrier shall provide coverage for and may not impose any
18 cost–sharing requirements, including copayments, coinsurance, or deductibles for:
19 (1) evidence–based items or services that have in effect a rating of A or B
20 in the recommendations of the United States Preventive Services Task Force with respect
21 to the individual involved;
22 (2) immunizations for routine use in children, adolescents, and adults that
23 have in effect a recommendation from the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices
24 of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention with respect to the individual involved,
25 if the recommendation:
26 (i) has been adopted by the Director of the Centers for Disease
27 Control and Prevention; or
28 (ii) is listed on the Immunization Schedules of the Centers for
29 Disease Control and Prevention for routine use;
30 (3) with respect to infants, children, and adolescents, evidence–informed
31 preventive care and screenings provided for in comprehensive guidelines supported by the
32 Health Resources and Services Administration; and
33 (4) with respect to women:

SENATE BILL 385 7
1 (i) to the extent not provided in item (ii) of this item, preventive care
2 and screenings as provided for in comprehensive guidelines supported by the Health
3 Resources and Services Administration for purposes of § 2713(a)(4) of the federal Public
4 Health Service Act; and
5 (ii) subject to § 15–826(c) of this title, contraceptive coverage as
6 provided for in comprehensive guidelines supported by the Health Resources and Services
7 Administration for purposes of § 2713(a)(4) of the federal Public Health Service Act.
8 (b) To the extent that cost–sharing is otherwise allowed under federal or State
9 law, a health benefit plan that uses a network of providers may impose cost–sharing
10 requirements on the coverage described in subsection (a) of this section for items or services
11 delivered by an out–of–network provider.
12 (c) (1) In this subsection, “high deductible health plan” has the meaning stated
13 in 26 U.S.C. § 223(c)(2).
14 (2) If an insured or enrollee is covered under a high deductible health plan,
15 a carrier may apply the deductible requirement of the high deductible health plan to the
16 coverage required under subsection (a) of this section, unless the Commissioner determines
17 that the coverage is included in the safe harbor provisions for preventive care under 26
18 U.S.C. § 223(c)(2)(c).
19 (d) This section may not be construed to prohibit a carrier from providing
20 coverage for services in addition to those recommended by the United States Preventive
21 Services Task Force or to deny coverage for services that are not recommended by the Task
22 Force.
23 (e) Subject to § 15–826(c) of this title[:
24 (1)], the Commissioner shall enforce this section consistent with the
25 recommendations and guidelines in effect on December 31, 2024, set by the United States
26 Preventive Services Task Force, the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices of the
27 Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, or the Health Resources and Services
28 Administration, and related federal rules or guidance[; and
29 (2) the Commissioner may adopt regulations:
30 (i) necessary to carry out this section, consistent with federal
31 statutes, rules, and guidance in effect:
32 1. on December 31, 2024; or
33 2. at a later date that enhance the scope of preventive
34 services to the benefit of consumers in the State; or

8 SENATE BILL 385
1 (ii) to require carriers to provide coverage without imposing
2 cost–sharing requirements, including copayments, coinsurance, or deductibles, for any
3 future preventive services recommendations and guidelines issued after December 31,
4 2024, by the United States Preventive Services Task Force, the Advisory Committee on
5 Immunization Practices of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, or the Health
6 Resources and Services Administration, and related federal rules or guidance], AS
7 UPDATED BY RECOMMENDATIONS ISSUED BY THE SECRETARY OF HEALTH IN
8 ACCORDANCE WITH § 18–112 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE.
9 (F) A CARRIER SHALL PROVIDE THE COVERAGE DESCRIBED IN SUBSECTION
10 (A) OF THIS SECTION FOR PLAN YEARS THAT BEGIN ON OR AFTER THE DATE THAT IS
11 3 MONTHS 1 YEAR AFTER THE DATE THE RECOMMENDATIONS DESCRIBED IN
12 SUBSECTION (E) OF THIS SECTION ARE ISSUED.
13 15–817.
14 (a) In this section, “child wellness services” means preventive activities designed
15 to protect children from morbidity and mortality and promote child development.
16 (b) This section applies to each individual hospital or major medical insurance
17 policy, group or blanket health insurance policy, and nonprofit health service plan that:
18 (1) is delivered or issued for delivery in the State;
19 (2) is written on an expense–incurred basis; and
20 (3) provides coverage for a family member of the insured.
21 (c) (1) A policy or plan subject to this section shall include under the family
22 member coverage a minimum package of child wellness services that are consistent with:
23 (i) public health policy;
24 (ii) professional standards; and
25 (iii) scientific evidence of effectiveness.
26 (2) The minimum package of child wellness services shall cover at least:
27 (i) all visits for and costs of childhood and adolescent immunizations
28 recommended by the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices of the Centers for
29 Disease Control and Prevention as of December 31, 2024, AS UPDATED BY
30 RECOMMENDATIONS ISSUED BY THE SECRETARY OF HEALTH IN ACCORDANCE WITH
31 § 18–112 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE;

SENATE BILL 385 9
1 (ii) visits for the collection of adequate samples, the first of which is
2 to be collected before 2 weeks of age, for hereditary and metabolic newborn screening and
3 follow–up between birth and 4 weeks of age;
4 (iii) universal hearing screening of newborns provided by a hospital
5 before discharge;
6 (iv) all visits for and costs of age–appropriate screening tests for
7 tuberculosis, anemia, lead toxicity, hearing, and vision as determined by the American
8 Academy of Pediatrics;
9 (v) all visits for obesity evaluation and management;
10 (vi) all visits for and costs of developmental screening as
11 recommended by the American Academy of Pediatrics;
12 (vii) a physical examination, developmental assessment, and
13 parental anticipatory guidance services at each of the visits required under items (i), (ii),
14 (iv), (v), and (vi) of this paragraph; and
15 (viii) any laboratory tests considered necessary by the physician as
16 indicated by the services provided under items (i), (ii), (iv), (v), (vi), or (vii) of this paragraph.
17 (d) Except as provided in subsection (e) of this section, an insurer or nonprofit
18 health service plan that issues a policy or plan subject to this section, on notification of the
19 pregnancy of the insured and before the delivery date, shall:
20 (1) encourage and help the insured to choose and contact a primary care
21 provider for the expected newborn before delivery; and
22 (2) provide the insured with information on postpartum home visits for the
23 mother and the expected newborn, including the names of health care providers that are
24 available for postpartum home visits.
25 (e) An insurer or nonprofit health service plan that does not require or encourage
26 the insured to use a particular health care provider or group of health care providers that
27 has contracted with the insurer or nonprofit health service plan to provide services to the
28 insurer’s or nonprofit health service plan’s insureds need not comply with subsection (d) of
29 this section.
30 (f) (1) A policy or plan subject to this section may not impose a deductible on
31 the coverage required under this section.
32 (2) Each health insurance policy and certificate shall contain a notice of the
33 prohibition established by paragraph (1) of this subsection in a form approved by the
34 Commissioner.

10 SENATE BILL 385
1 (g) The Commissioner may adopt regulations necessary to carry out subsection
2 (c)(2)(i) of this section consistent with federal statutes, rules, and guidance in effect[:
3 (1)] on December 31, 2024[; or
4 (2) at a later date to account for any new vaccines recommended by the
5 Centers for Disease Control and Prevention’s Advisory Committee on Immunization
6 Practices after December 31, 2024], AS UPDATED BY RECOMMENDATIONS ISSUED BY
7 THE SECRETARY OF HEALTH IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 18–112 OF THE
8 HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE.
9 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall apply to all
10 policies, contracts, and health benefit plans issued, delivered, or renewed in the State on or
11 after January 1, 2027.
12 SECTION 4. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
13 1, 2026.
Approved:
